KEY ISSUES with the dataset

  • Observation and Variable Amount:the amount of observations in certain dataset may be too extraneous or too little for the analysis, same as varibles. To avoid overfit related issues when building models, feature selection will be conducted based on approriate amount of observations. Once we have the daily data, the extraction for monthly or quarterly report would be simple.

  • Missing Values:missing values exists in several variables arise when reocorded data has different frequency i.e daily, monthly, quarterly, and annually. Our approach is to turn all variables to daily then fill in missing value using latest observation by date.

  • Inapproriate Data Frame:to merge all 3 datasets together, they must have the same dataframe with at least a common column-in this case, it is column Date. After examination of the dataset structure, data1 and data2 are appropriate to be merged. However this doesn’t apply to data3, the dataframe doesn’t reflect the same structure as other two dataset. Each ticker in data3 that has different campo and value by date that must be transposed in an alike formation to data1 and dat2, in which all macro indices are identified as variables not observations.

II. Dataset Preparation

IMPUTING MISSING DATES & VALUES

Since data2 contains the dependent variables which are all AFP Habitat’s current assets. Let’s take a look at their recording period. The min and max date will be the time stamp for all dataset.

PREPARE DATASET ‘data2’

#turn dataset to daily and fill in missing values with previous observation
library(imputeTS)
data2 <- data2 %>%
  complete(Date = seq.Date(min(Date), max(Date), by="day")) %>%
  na_locf(.)
data2 <- as.data.frame(data2)
